ratings.question_text: What is your overall assessment of this course?

narratives.question_text: How would you summarize AFAM 505 01/AMST 643 01 for a fellow student? Would you recommend AFAM 505 01/AMST 643 01 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: Yes, surely. This is a nice combination of math and policy making course

A "materials physics" course designed to incorporate some semiconductor-related topics that are not encompassed in other classes. Or also "materials concepts as seen by electrical engineers."Yes, I would recommend this course to other engineering students; the instructor is good, and the workload is not overwhelming.
Yes, I would. Because if the student is microelectronics track in EE, I would say the materials covered would really help to widen our view.
The course is helpful for you to know different fields.
It is a good course and I will recommend it to others.

narratives.question_text: How did this course deepen your knowledge of your discipline/profession? To what extent did this course contribute to your dissertation/research?
comments: Yes, I learnt a lot that I would not have otherwise
The class contents was not my field exactly, but it is helpful.

The course helped increase my knowledge of the semiconductor profession by exposing me to several concepts that I have been able to integrate into my job in the semiconductor industry, as well as building a sufficient background into concepts that will prove a strong foundation for future developments.
It offered a look into concepts not usually covered in an EE course.
In terms of deepen, I would rather say widen.
It broadens my knowledge on other applications of semiconductors besides logic applications
